gurudvaaraa paaNvttaa saahib sikh dhrm kaa ek puujniiy tiirthsthl hai /  yh pvitr mNdir n kevl aadhyaatmik aaraam prdaan krtaa hai, blki hmeN yh bhii btaataa hai ki sikh dhrm kaise kaaym hai /  is sthaan kaa naam yaa to is tthy se pdd'aa ki guru gobiNd siNh ne yhaaN apne pair rkhe the yaa islie ki unkaa ek aabhuussnn yhaaN kho gyaa thaa jise vh apne pair meN phnte the / 
khaaniyoN ke anusaar, gurudvaare meN ek baar sikhoN ke dsveN guru, guru gobiNd siNh jii ne dauraa kiyaa thaa /  sikh guru raajaa medinii prkaash ke nimNtrnn pr sirmaur aae aur raajaa ke shissttaacaar se itne prbhaavit hue ki unhoNne agle caar saal poNttaa meN bitaane kaa phaislaa kiyaa aur raajy meN apne jiivn kaa ek likhit vivrnn chodd'aa, jiskaa unhoNne vrnnn kiyaa unke jiivn ke sbse sukhd vrssoN ke ruup meN / 
pauNttaa saahib gurudvaaraa
aisaa khaa jaataa hai ki, ek baar raajaa medinii prkaash aur guru jii is sthaan kii khoj kr rhe the /  apne bhrmnn ke dauraan gurujii itne prbhaavit hue ki unhoNne ndii ke ttt pr ek shivir bnaane kaa nirnny liyaa /  gurujii ne apne jkhmii haathoN se is pvitr shhr kii niiNv rkhii aur iskaa naam paun-ttikkaa rkhaa, jo aaj paaNvttaa saahib ke naam se jaanaa jaataa hai /  smmaan aur kRtjnytaa ke prtiik ke ruup meN, raajaa medinii prkaash ne ymunaa ndii ke ttt pr ek gurudvaaraa bnaane kaa phaislaa kiyaa /  gurudvaaraa chodd'ne se phle, gurujii ne kuch pdd'osii bstiyoN ke khilaaph kii ldd'aaiyaaN ldd'iiN / 
gurudvaare kii vrtmaan sNrcnaa kaa nirmaann 1823 meN baabaa kpuur siNh dvaaraa kiyaa gyaa thaa /  phle, yh mNdir ghne aur susvaadu jNgl ke biic meN sthit thaa, jhaaN guru gobiNd siNh jii shikaar krte the, apne yoddhaaoN ko prshikssit krte the aur saahity kii kitaabeN likhte the /  guru gobiNd siNh ne yhaaN kii mhtvpuurnn pvitr pustkeN likhiiN, jinmeN dshm grNth kaa prmukh bhaag bhii shaamil hai /  phir vh khaalsaa pNth kii sthaapnaa ke lie aanNdpur saahib cle ge / 
gurudvaare ke aNdr ek bdd'aa drbaar hai jhaaN guru apne 52 kviyoN ke saath baitthte the /  any prmukh aakrssnn haiN shrii taalaab asthaan aur shrii daastaan asthaan; shrii taalaab asthaan meN vetn vitrit kiyaa jaataa hai, aur shrii taalaab asthaan meN pgdd'ii baaNdho prtiyogitaa aayojit kii jaatii hai /  iske alaavaa yhaaN ek sNgrhaaly bhii hai jhaaN gurujii ke vibhinn hthiyaar prdrshit haiN / 
mNdir ke piiche ndii ttt pr ymunaa jii kaa aitihaasik mNdir hai aur iske alaavaa maaN ymunaa baal paark bhii hai /  gurudvaaraa paaNvttaa saahib ke paas hii gurudvaaraa shrii kvi drbaar saahib hai jhaaN hr saal kvitaa paatth prtiyogitaa kaa aayojn kiyaa jaataa hai /  sikh tiirthyaatrii hr smy yhaaN aate rhte haiN, aur bhkti giit prisr meN guuNjte haiN, jo ciNtnshiil mnodshaa ko jodd'te haiN /  tiirthyaatrii yhaaN aadhyaatmik saaNtvnaa paane ke lie aate haiN /

featured_reviews.review_translated_text:
Gurdwara Paonta Sahib is a revered pilgrimage center of Sikhism. This holy shrine not only provides spiritual comfort, but also tells us how Sikhism is sustained. The place got its name either from the fact that Guru Gobind Singh had placed his feet here or because one of his ornaments which he used to wear on his feet was lost here.
As per the stories, the Gurdwara was once visited by the tenth Guru of the Sikhs, Guru Gobind Singh Ji. The Sikh Guru came to Sirmaur at the invitation of Raja Medini Prakash and was so impressed by the Raja's courtesy that he decided to spend the next four years at Ponta and left a written account of his life in the kingdom, which he described as the happiest years of his life. In form of.
Paonta Sahib Gurudwara
It is said that, once King Medini Prakash and Guru Ji were searching for this place. Guruji was so impressed during his visit that he decided to set up a camp on the banks of the river. Guruji laid the foundation of this holy city with his wounded hands and named it Paun-Tikka, which is today known as Paonta Sahib. As a mark of respect and gratitude, Raja Medini Prakash decided to build a Gurudwara on the banks of the Yamuna River. Before leaving the Gurudwara, Guruji fought several battles against some neighboring settlements.
The present structure of the Gurdwara was built in 1823 by Baba Kapoor Singh. Earlier, this temple was situated in the middle of a dense and luscious forest, where Guru Gobind Singh Ji used to hunt, train his warriors and write books of literature. Guru Gobind Singh wrote several important holy books here, including a major portion of the Dasam Granth. He then moved to Anandpur Sahib to establish the Khalsa Panth.
Inside the Gurdwara is a large court where the Guru used to sit with his 52 poets. Other major attractions are Shri Talab Asthan and Shri Dastan Asthan; Salary is distributed at Shri Talab Asthan, and Turban Bandho competition is organized at Shri Talab Asthan. Apart from this, there is also a museum where various weapons of Guruji are displayed.
Behind the temple, there is a historical temple of Yamuna ji on the river bank and apart from this there is also Maa Yamuna Child Park. Near Gurudwara Paonta Sahib is Gurudwara Shri Kavi Darbar Sahib where poetry recitation competition is organized every year. Sikh pilgrims come here all the time, and devotional songs echo through the complex, adding to the contemplative mood. Pilgrims come here to find spiritual solace.

featured_reviews.review_id:
Paonta Sahib Gurudwara is of historic significance to the pious Sikhs, as the 10th Sikh guru Govind Singh had stayed here and written religious scriptures.
The Gurudwara is located on the banks of river Yamuna and its said that the guru had asked Yamuna to flow calmly without noise as it distracted the guru writing the Holi scriptures.
The very clean and tidy interiors of the Gurudwara brings peace to the minds of devotees sitting inside.
There are other buildings surrounding the main Gurudwara such as the Guru ka lunger hall, the Sheesh mahal etc. Sikhs get their kids marry in adjoining hall with religious gurus blessings the newly weds.
The visitors are given special Kada prashad before they leave the premises.
A must visit Gurudwara- amongst the most revered by the Sikhs.
